# Backend Architecture — Controller / Service / Repository

## Layer Responsibilities (strict separation — never cross layers)

```
HTTP Request
    ↓
[ Controller ]   → validates HTTP input, calls service, sends HTTP response
    ↓
[  Service   ]   → business logic, orchestrates repositories, throws domain errors
    ↓
[ Repository ]   → Prisma Client queries only, returns raw entities
    ↓
[ Prisma Client ]
    ↓
[ Neon PostgreSQL ]
```

### Controller Rules
- **Only** handle: parse request → validate → call service → format response
- Never write SQL or business logic in a controller
- Always return the standard response envelope (see below)
- File: `src/controllers/[resource]Controller.ts`

```typescript
// ✅ Correct controller
export const getArticle = async (req: Request, res: Response): Promise<void> => {
  const { id } = req.params;
  const article = await articleService.getPublishedById(id);
  res.json(successResponse(article));
};

// ❌ Wrong — business logic AND direct Prisma access in controller
export const getArticle = async (req: Request, res: Response): Promise<void> => {
  const article = await prisma.article.findUnique({ where: { id: req.params.id } });
  if (article.status !== 'Published') throw new Error('Not found');
  res.json(article);
};
```

### Service Rules
- Contains **all** business logic and state transitions
- Calls only repositories (never `db` directly)
- Throws typed `AppError` instances — never `new Error()`
- File: `src/services/[resource]Service.ts`

```typescript
// ✅ Correct service
export class ArticleService {
  async getPublishedById(id: string): Promise<Article> {
    const article = await articleRepository.findById(id);
    if (!article) throw new AppError('Article not found', 404);
    if (article.status !== 'Published') throw new AppError('Article not available', 403);
    return article;
  }
}
```

### Repository Rules
- **Only** database queries — no business logic, no HTTP concepts
- **Prisma ORM only** — all queries go through the generated Prisma Client (`prisma.[model].findUnique/findMany/create/update/...`). Never build raw SQL strings.
- If a query genuinely can't be expressed through Prisma's query API (rare — e.g. a complex aggregation), use `prisma.$queryRaw` with a **tagged template literal** (never `$queryRawUnsafe`, never string concatenation) — see `04-database-conventions.mdc`.
- Return plain entity objects or `null` — never throw HTTP errors
- File: `src/repositories/[resource]Repository.ts`

```typescript
// ✅ Correct repository
import { prisma } from '../db/prisma';

export class ArticleRepository {
  async findById(id: string): Promise<Article | null> {
    return prisma.article.findFirst({
      where: { id, deletedAt: null },
    });
  }
}
```

## Standard API Response Envelope
Every API response must use this shape — no exceptions:

```typescript
// src/types/api.types.ts
interface ApiResponse<T = undefined> {
  success: boolean;
  data?: T;
  message?: string;
  error?: string;
}

// Success helper
const successResponse = <T>(data: T, message?: string): ApiResponse<T> => ({
  success: true,
  data,
  message,
});

// Error helper
const errorResponse = (error: string): ApiResponse => ({
  success: false,
  error,
});
```

## Custom Error Class
```typescript
// src/errors/AppError.ts
export class AppError extends Error {
  constructor(
    public message: string,
    public statusCode: number = 500,
    public code?: string
  ) {
    super(message);
    this.name = 'AppError';
  }
}
```

## Global Error Middleware (place last in Express chain)
```typescript
// src/middleware/errorHandler.ts
export const errorHandler = (
  err: Error,
  req: Request,
  res: Response,
  next: NextFunction
): void => {
  if (err instanceof AppError) {
    res.status(err.statusCode).json(errorResponse(err.message));
    return;
  }
  logger.error('Unhandled error', { err, path: req.path });
  res.status(500).json(errorResponse('Internal server error'));
};
```

## Route File Pattern
```typescript
// src/routes/articles.routes.ts
import { Router } from 'express';
import { authenticate } from '../middleware/auth.middleware';
import { requireRole } from '../middleware/rbac.middleware';
import * as articleController from '../controllers/articleController';

const router = Router();

router.get('/', articleController.listPublished);
router.get('/mine', authenticate, articleController.listOwn);
router.get('/:id', articleController.getById);
router.post('/', authenticate, articleController.create);
router.patch('/:id', authenticate, articleController.update);
router.delete('/:id', authenticate, articleController.remove);

export default router;
```

## File Structure (backend)
```
src/
  controllers/
    articleController.ts
    authController.ts
    ...
  services/
    articleService.ts
    authService.ts
    ...
  repositories/
    articleRepository.ts
    userRepository.ts
    ...
  routes/
    articlesRoutes.ts
    authRoutes.ts
    index.ts          ← mounts all routers at /api/v1/...
  middleware/
    authMiddleware.ts
    rbacMiddleware.ts
    errorHandler.ts
    validateMiddleware.ts
  types/
    apiTypes.ts
    articleTypes.ts
    userTypes.ts
    ...
  errors/
    AppError.ts
  config/
    env.ts
  db/
    prisma.ts        ← exports the singleton PrismaClient — import this, never `new PrismaClient()` elsewhere
prisma/
  schema.prisma       ← Prisma schema (models, enums, relations) — see 04-database-conventions.mdc
  migrations/          ← generated by `prisma migrate dev`, never hand-edited
  seed.ts
```
